  "description": "Tullia Benedicta grew up in Ravenna in a Neapolitan family, which is to say she grew up inside two Italys at once. The North that never asked where she",
  "image_alt": "NZIRIA And The Sound With No Border",
  "body": "Tullia Benedicta grew up in Ravenna in a Neapolitan family, which is to say she grew up inside two Italys at once. The North that never asked where she came from. The South that was always asking where she had gone. NZIRIA, the project she releases under, is what happens when a producer decides not to choose between those Italys but to slam them together at full volume.\n\n[spotify:artist/4bt8JAxE4tksg2VBgMCvIe]\n\nShe calls the genre Hard Neomelodico. It pulls from neomelodica, the working-class Neapolitan pop that scores weddings and funerals and the long slow late-night walks home, and runs it through gabber, hardcore, and the kind of distortion that makes the speaker cone visibly move. Her debut XXYBRID came out on Gabber Eleganza's Never Sleep imprint. ULTRANCE followed and pushed even further into the red.\n\n## What Hard Neomelodico Actually Is\n\nNeomelodica is a genre that the Italian cultural establishment has spent decades trying to ignore. It is music of the working-class south, of Campania and the Naples suburbs, of communities that do not appear in the official narrative of Italian culture as sophisticated or worthy of serious attention. The melodies are emotionally direct to the point of excess. The lyrics deal in uncomplicated feeling: love, loss, loyalty, the particular solidarity of people who understand that official society has no particular interest in them.\n\nGabber comes from Rotterdam, from the early 1990s hardcore rave scene, and it shares with neomelodica a quality that both traditions' critics reach for the same word to dismiss: vulgarity. Both genres are loud in the wrong registers, emotionally unsubtle in ways that cultured taste finds embarrassing, made for and by communities that do not factor into the mainstream's self-image.\n\nWhen NZIRIA puts them together, the collision produces something that is not a novelty act. The emotional logic of both forms is identical. Both are about the intensity of feeling without apology. Both are anti-ironic in a cultural moment that treats irony as sophistication. The production just makes the argument at a volume where it cannot be dismissed.\n\n## The Vocal as Proof\n\nWhat makes her work particular is the vocal. She sings the way nonna sings on a Sunday, full chest, slightly cracked, completely sincere. Then the kick drum hits at 180 BPM and you realise she is doing something nobody else is. There is no distance between the tradition and the rave. They are the same song.\n\nThe voice is not processed into something alien. It is recognisably human, recognisably from a specific tradition, recognisably in relationship with the machines underneath it rather than buried by them. This is the key decision in the whole project. A different producer might have treated the neomelodica vocal as a sample to be chopped and repitched. NZIRIA treats it as the primary instrument and builds the production around what it needs.\n\n## Live and in the Room\n\nLive she is a presence. The Boiler Room set she did last year was one of those clips that goes round group chats for three days. People DJing in T-shirts that say MAMMA. Someone crying in the front row. Someone else laughing at the same time. That is the territory she works in, the place where the joke and the prayer are the same gesture.\n\nThe experience of the live set makes clear what the recordings suggest: this music is designed to be felt physically. The kick drum in gabber is not a rhythmic event. It is a physical event. At proper volume it reorganises your relationship to your own body. NZIRIA uses this physiological dimension to deliver emotional content that the lyric alone could not carry to the same place.\n\n## The Non-Binary Dimension\n\nThe non-binary thing matters here too. She has been clear that the project is about borderlessness as a lived experience, not as an aesthetic. North/South. Masculine/feminine. Tradition/contemporary. The hyphen is the point. The refusal to resolve the contradictions is the artistic position.\n\nIn a cultural moment where identity claims often harden into brand positions, NZIRIA's approach is genuinely dialectical. The categories remain in tension. The tension is productive. The music sounds like what it feels like to live inside multiple contradictions simultaneously without needing them to resolve.\n\nNZIRIA is what new Italian music sounds like when it stops asking permission. Start with XXYBRID, then ULTRANCE, then go listen to your grandmother's records again.\n\n[download:/assets/images/artists/nziria-hard-neomelodico-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]"
}
ENDJSON
